        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 11:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "θυσίας καὶ προσφοράς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The plural appropriately serves for the generalization of the utterance.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αἵτινες κατὰ νόμον προσφέρονται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as those things which are presented by virtue of legal precept",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Suggestive reference to the imperfection and ineffectiveness of Judaism, since this makes salvation dependent precisely upon those ordinances of external sacrifice which God willed not, and in which He has no pleasure. The words are no parenthetic clause, as is still maintained by Bleek and Kurtz, but an addition essential to the argument of the writer, which does not interrupt the construction. They form ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the application",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", thus emphatically appended, of the first half of the thought in the Scripture citation, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to Judaism",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to which the parallel is formed in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 10:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the application",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the second half ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
