  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 10:8-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἀνώτερον λέγων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τότε εἴρηκεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Above, when He said—then said He",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Paul urges the order of the words of the psalm which depends on the particle, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "אז",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τότε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", then, showing that it falls on that very time when the prophet sang the psalm in the character of Christ, and on that very point of time when, immediately after the words, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "θυσίαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., sacrifice, etc., placed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀνώτερον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", above, in the psalm, there sprang up the words, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἰδοὺ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἥκω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", lo! I come. Therefore ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "אז",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is altogether demonstrative of the present (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "אז",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τότε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", then, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 69:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), with an antithesis between the things concerned, from which the wisdom of the apostle infers the first and second, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "אז",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 10:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); comp.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μετὰ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", after, ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 7:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", note. Let this ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "אז",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " be the terminus (the point of boundary between the Old and New Testament). Paul also puts, in the first place, the general word of the LXX., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εἶπον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", then one more significant, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εἴρηκεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; whence it is evident, that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λέγων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", saying, is of the imperfect tense [when He said, or was saying]. But observe how great authority the Psalms possess. The oath of Jehovah was given at the very time when Psalms 110 was written. The solemn invitation was issued to the people when Psalms 95 was written; ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 4:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 7:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", note. The declaration of the Son was made when Psalms 2 was written; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 13:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", note. So, the Messiah promised to GOD that He would do His will, at the time when Psalms 40 was written. This handwriting, which David executed, is opposed to the law written by Moses; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 10:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", at the end. Wherefore Christ always appealed with the greatest force to the Scriptures, and especially at the beginning of His passion.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κατὰ τὸν νόμον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", according to the law) The strong argument by which that very point which is asserted in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 10:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is proved from the psalm.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 8-10.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Saying above that Sacrifices and offerings and whole burnt offerings and offerings for sin thou wouldest not, neither hadst pleasure therein",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (such as are offered according to the Law); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "then hath he said, Lo, I come to do thy will; i.e. he has made this second assertion while making the first also.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "then hath he said, Lo, I come to do thy will; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "accented",
            "text": "i.e.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " he has made this second assertion while making the first also.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The purpose of thus putting it is to show the connection between the two assertions; that fulfillment of God's will is spoken of as a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "substitute",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for sacrifices, whose inutility in themselves had been declared. Yes; he taketh away the first, that he may establish the second. In the which will (the Divine will, willing our redemption through Christ, and perfectly fulfilled by him) we have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all. For the sense to be attached to the verb ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἁγιάζω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " see under Hebrews 2:11. It is not our progressive sanctification by the Holy Ghost that is intended, but the hallowing effected for us once for all, as denoted by the perfect participle ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἡγιασμένοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The remainder of this concluding summary (vers. 11-19) serves to weave together the various threads of the foregoing argument and emphasize the result. Hebrews 10:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
